Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

```csharp
// McpIntegrationTests.cs
public class McpTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        // initialize first, then list tools
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };
        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }

    private async Task InitializeSession() { /* send initialize + initialized */ }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **No real port** — `WebApplicationFactory` uses an in-memory test server (`TestServer`).
- **Full pipeline** — middleware, routing, DI, and serialization all run as in production.
- **Override services** — use `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in mocks (e.g., fake data stores).
- **SSE transport** — if your server uses SSE, read the response stream with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and parse `text/event-stream` lines manually.
- **Stateful sessions** — if MCP state is per-connection, consider creating a fresh `HttpClient` per test or using session headers/cookies.
